{"id":"1601.07673","submitter":"Vadim Nikolayev","authors":"Vadim Nikolayev (SPEC - UMR), D Beysens (SBT - UMR, PMMH), Y Garrabos\n  (ICMCB), C Lecoutre (ICMCB), D Chatain (SBT - UMR)","title":"Bubble spreading during the boiling crisis: modelling and experimenting\n  in microgravity","comments":"arXiv admin note: text overlap with arXiv:0707.3009, Microgravity\n  Sciences and Technology, 2006","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/BF02870375","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn physics.class-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Boiling is a very efficient way to transfer heat from a heater to the liquid\ncarrier. We discuss the boiling crisis, a transition between two regimes of\nboiling: nucleate and film boiling. The boiling crisis results in a sharp\ndecrease in the heat transfer rate, which can cause a major accident in\nindustrial heat exchangers. In this communication, we present a physical model\nof the boiling crisis based on the vapor recoil effect. Under the action of the\nvapor recoil the gas bubbles begin to spread over the heater thus forming a\ngerm for the vapor film. The vapor recoil force not only causes its spreading,\nit also creates a strong adhesion to the heater that prevents the bubble\ndeparture, thus favoring the further spreading. Near the liquid-gas critical\npoint, the bubble growth is very slow and allows the kinetics of the bubble\nspreading to be observed. Since the surface tension is very small in this\nregime, only microgravity conditions can preserve a convex bubble shape. In the\nexperiments both in the Mir space station and in the magnetic levitation\nfacility, we directly observed an increase of the apparent contact angle and\nspreading of the dry spot under the bubble. Numerical simulations of the\nthermally controlled bubble growth show this vapor recoil effect too thus\nconfirming our model of the boiling crisis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 28 Jan 2016 07:37:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-01-29"}
